<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-669-605  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 669 605.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>InfoWorld  Dec 10 1990 v12 n50 p45(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft boosts its investment in natural language. (MicrosoftCorp. increases investment in Natural Language Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mace, Scott.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microsoft Corp has invested an additional $1 million in NaturalLanguage Inc (NLI), a Berkeley, CA company acknowledged as theleading vendor of natural language technology for relationaldatabases.andP;  The two companies are jointly developing interfacesthat will allow users of future Microsoft products to access databases with English commands.andP;  Natural Language officials say thatthe move into natural language DBMS technology is a logical nextstep for Microsoft, which is moving beyond the graphical userinterface metaphor in its efforts to make computers easier to use.andO;Microsoft invested $1.5 million in NLI in 1987 to supportdevelopment of Windows and 32-bit OS/2 versions of the NLIdatabase tool set.andP;  NLI tools can access Oracle, Ingres, Informix,Rdb and other major databases.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Investment activities)Natural Language Inc. (Investor relations).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     Computer IndustryInvestmentsNatural Language InterfacesSoftware PublishersRelational DBMSNew TechniqueData Base Management Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>